main event: On 18 October 1956, a ground-visual observation reported a bright light group showing intense yellow color that flared up, dropped straight down, and flared up again, moving at a high rate of speed to the west.
interesting points: The sighting caused considerable excitement, indicating the unusual nature of the event.
The light group seemed to fire and burn out, behaving in a way that did not resemble conventional aircraft.
The conclusions listed possibilities such as balloon, aircraft, and astronomical phenomena, suggesting uncertainty in identifying the object.
The document includes a pilot report indicating a sighting of a round, burning, light green object surrounded by smoke, heading from east to west at a high altitude.
The pilot report also emphasizes the intense brightness and unusual movement of the observed object, adding to the mystery.
sighted object: unidentified bright light group, round burning light green object
photographs: No, the report does not include photographs
